 type="geneprod" role="component">Rad53</sd-pretag> are activated through phosphorylation, including phosphorylation at <sd-pretag id="sdPretag771649971sd" parent-gene-tag-id="54" parent-protein-tag-id="11">Mec1</sd-pretag>-S1991. <sd-pretag id="sdPretag120935979sd" parent-gene-tag-id="54" parent-protein-tag-id="11">Mec1</sd-pretag>-S1991 phosphorylation is not required to activate the downstream checkpoint effector kinase <sd-pretag id="sdPretag1175445235sd" type="geneprod" role="component">Rad53</sd-pretag>, yet it promotes the attenuation of RNAPII and RNAPIII-mediated transcription during replication stress, acting on a variety of transcription controlling factors. Proteasome-mediated RNAPII degradation during replication stress requires a functional <sd-pretag id="sdPretag938705741sd" type="geneprod" role="component">Cul3</sd-pretag>-Elc1 <sd-pretag id="sdPretag1393381059sd" type="geneprod" role="component">ubiquitin</sd-pretag> ligase. RNAPIII is evicted in a <sd-pretag id="sdPretag2126744118sd" parent-gene-tag-id="54" parent-protein-tag-id="11">Mec1</sd-pretag>-dependent manner but not degraded. <sd-pretag id="sdPretag1582320894sd" parent-gene-tag-id="54" parent-protein-tag-id="11">Mec1</sd-pretag>-induced RNAPII removal from <sd-pretag id="sdPretag46559370sd" parent-tag-id="68">chromatin</sd-pretag> allows the release of highly transcribed genes from nuclear <sd-pretag id="sdPretag1661993264sd" type="subcellular" role="component">pore</sd-pretag> under HU stress, while <sd-pretag id="sdPretag517084541sd" type="geneprod" role="component">Rad53</sd-pretag> is thought to <sd-pretag id="sdPretag1314643362sd" type="geneprod" role="component">act</sd-pretag> directly on the nuclear pores complex (<sd-pretag id="sdPretag580635587sd" type="cell" role="component">NPC</sd-pretag>). <graphic href="https://api.sourcedata.io/file.php?panel_id=118738"/></sd-panel></fig></article>